While many restaurants are trying to navigate a tricky and ever-changing pandemic landscape, Carma's has been a local blessing. They are a small eatery in the basement of an apartment building at the corner of St. Paul St & 32nd St.  But it's unique location is only enhanced by the small "mom&pop" vibe and it's eccentricly tasteful menu. My wife and I have purchased cuisine from here many times in the past 9 years, and we've enjoyed what we've ordered. They have entrees and desserts and drinks and even jams and apple butter!  And, back in March or April (of 2020 when everything was shut down for COVID-19, and it was difficult to locate the basics in grocery stores), they posted that they had eggs for sale, and we needed some, so we went and purchased eggs from them! We also loved that it was both supporting a local, and it was also supporting a local farmer.  This place is one of our faces, and we'll continue to visit.

This place serves some good food that’s fresh and yummy. The staff members are nice and sweet. What makes me extremely upset is the conditions those people work in. The sink next to their main coffee machine is broken and doesn’t function at all. So the employees put a big bucket underneath the sink that collects all the water and then the same employees have to carry that heavy bucket to the back room to empty it. The other day I saw a very petite young girl emptying that bucket - it was extremely heavy for her, so she had to split the dirty water in half and make a few trips to the back room. If the bucket gets overfilled and the liquid spills over, the employees have to clean the floor. They do not do it after work but every hour or so, as soon as the bucket gets filled. Moreover, only two grills function properly in their back room, and because of that the wait for your order in any rush hour could be around 35 minutes. The place itself is worn out and needs some renovation. I bet if the employees put a jar with a sign “donations to re-paint this room”, they would have the money to buy enough paint in a few days. What makes me even more upset is that the owner of this cafe hasn’t done anything to fix any of the problems I’ve mentioned here. I go to this place almost every day, because they serve really good food, but the conditions inside and how much its employees struggle to keep this place running make me shocked and disappointed. ( I will be happy to edit my review after I see the plan of action made by the owner becomes real.)

I used to work there. one morning, I came in and the main line fridge wasn't working, all the other workers were baffled about what to do. so finally the owner came in and he had us remove all of the stuff that was stored overnight on the main line fridge into a beverage cooler. I knew some of the stuff was bad so he just performed a simple smell test. I'll never forget the moment when he smelled the sour cream and said it smells sour. it's fine. I ended fixing the fridge by replacing the power port, saving an easy $200 repair bill, did I get a bonus, no. all I got was a good job, now get back to work.

Carma catered two meals for our daughter's graduation family gathering at our rental and truly went above and beyond. She wanted to know what our graduate liked and get to know her before suggesting a menu. She cared deeply about the quality of the food, inconveniencing herself for both mealtimes so the food would be fresher (grilled cheese, just-out-of-the-oven scones). For a light supper after a big lunch and afternoon receptions, we chose BLT salad, grilled cheese and tomato soup. The plan was that Carma would deliver this meal and our brunch items for the following morning, but she wanted to bring her portable griddle and prepare the grilled cheese on site so the sandwiches wouldn't be soggy. For brunch we selected two types of fritata, fruit salad, bacon, my grad's two favorite types of scones, which coincidentally were the flavors that Carma won't allow anyone else on staff to make. Carma suggested a health bread that she makes and brought along a jar of her homemade blueberry lemon jam. Carma had decided she wanted to bake our scones fresh that morning, so this meant another delivery back to our rental. Just before her arrival, I asked if she could serve and clean up for an extra fee so I could relax and enjoy our party and get off to commencement more easily, and she moved her staff around at the cafe to accommodate her being with us all morning. If I ever give a party in Baltimore again, I know exactly who will be catering it! Don't think twice about booking her, but do it early because growth is not her goal -- quality is.
